{"title_page": "David Weston (actor)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n'''David Weston''' (born 28 July 1938, [[London]]) is an English actor, director and author. Since graduating from [[RADA]] in 1961<ref>{{Cite web|title=RADA Graduate Directory |url=http://www.rada.org/alumni/directory.aspx?id=108&frm=y&sur=Weston&nme=David&sub=&ttl=&yr= |accessdate=4 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210010757/http://www.rada.org/alumni/directory.aspx?id=108 |archivedate=10 February 2010 }}</ref> (having won the Silver Medal for that year)<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Awards at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\n  | page = 15\n  | newspaper = The Times\n  | location = London\n  | date = 21 July 1961\n}}</ref> he has acted in numerous film, television and stage productions, including twenty-seven plays in [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s canon and prominent guest roles in two [[Doctor Who]] serials. With [[Michael Croft]] he was a founder member of the [[National Youth Theatre]].<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Jardine\n  | first = Cassandra\n  | title = A new HQ honours the National Youth Theatre's founder\n  | pages =\n  | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph\n  | location = London\n  | date = 28 February 2009\n}}</ref> Much of his directing work has been for that organisation; he has directed also at the [[Regent's Park]] [[Regent's Park Open Air Theatre|Open Air Theatre]] and a number of other theatres in London. He wrote and narrated a series of non-fiction audio books, including ''Shakespeare His Life and Work'' which won the 2001 [https://web.archive.org/web/20090202124736/http://ibpa-online.org/custom/benfranklin/benfranklin.aspx Benjamin Franklin Award] for best audio non-fiction book.\n\n''Italic text''==Early career==\nWeston was educated at [[Alleyn's School]], [[Dulwich]], during the time that Michael Croft, founder of the [[National Youth Theatre]], was there creating drama of a very high standard.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Edward Alleyn Club - Theatre |url=http://www.edwardalleynclub.com/en/Theatre/ |accessdate=7 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126054710/http://www.edwardalleynclub.com/en/Theatre/ |archivedate=26 November 2009 }}</ref> In 1956 Croft directed a school production of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]]'', which, when revived as a [[National Youth Theatre|NYT]] production at the [[Toynbee Hall]] Theatre the following year, attracted the attention of the national press. Weston played [[Falstaff]], a character singled out by ''[[The Times]]'' in its praise of the play's comedy.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Youth Theatre\n  | pages = 3\n  | newspaper = The Times\n  | location = London\n  | date = 23 April 1957\n}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1960 Weston played Mark Antony in Shakespeare's ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'' at the [[Queen's Theatre]], [[Shaftesbury Avenue]]. Directed by Croft and given in [[modern dress]], this was only the second appearance by the company of the [[National Youth Theatre|NYT]] in [[West End of London|London's West End]]. [[John Shrapnel]] played Caesar, Neil Stacy Brutus and Alan Allkins Cassius. The play was judged a \"youthful success\" by the theatre critic of ''[[The Times]]''; Weston's performance was said to have successfully caught an opportunist spirit effectually hidden by a rough charm.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Modern Dress Caesar\n  | pages =\n  | newspaper = The Times\n  | location = London\n  | date = 12 August 1960\n}}</ref>\n\n''[After a season at Manchester Library Theatre under David Scase, Weston's first television appearance was as Romeo in a production for schools of Shakespeare's [[Romeo and Juliet]]; opposite [[Jane Asher's]] Juliet.<ref>{ Throughout the 1960s he played leading roles in wide variety of films: Becket, Heroes of Telemark, Doctor In Distress, Witchcraft, Masque of the Red Death, as well as the title role in Disney's Young Dick Turpin. He spent many years with the RCS and the National and appeared in many television plays and series such as Z Cars, Softly Softly, Special Branch, Minder, General Hospital, EastEnders and Doctors.\n |url         = http://www.recons.com/biogs/weston.htm\n |accessdate  = 4 February 2010\n |url-status     = dead \n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100111181808/http://www.recons.com/biogs/weston.htm\n |archivedate = 11 January 2010\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nIn 2011 Weston published ''Covering McKellen: An Understudy's Tale'', a memoir of the year he spent as [[Ian McKellen]]'s understudy in the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]'s tour of [[King Lear]] directed by [[Sir Trevor Nunn]].<ref>{{Cite book\n  | title = Covering McKellen: An Understudy's Tale\n  | last = Weston\n  | first = David\n  | year = 2011\n  | publisher = Rickshaw Publishing \n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-9565368-0-8}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Weston published ''Covering Shakespeare: An Actor's Saga of Near Misses and Dogged Endurance'', a memoir of his experiences performing in productions of Shakespeare's plays.<ref>{{Cite book\n  | title = Covering Shakespeare: An Actor's Saga of Near Misses and Dogged Endurance\n  | last = Weston\n  | first = David\n  | year = 2014\n  | publisher = Oberon Books\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-1783190645}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[That Kind of Girl]]'' (1963) - Keith Murray\n* ''[[Doctor in Distress (film)|Doctor In Distress]]'' (1963) - Dr Bell\n* ''[[80,000 Suspects]]'' (1963) - Brian Davis (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Informers (1963 film)|The Informers]]'' (1963) - Young constable (uncredited)\n* ''[[Witchcraft (1964 film)|Witchcraft]]'' (1964) - Todd Lanier\n* ''[[Becket (1964 film)|Becket]]'' (1964) - Brother John\n* ''[[The Masque of the Red Death (1964 film)|The Masque of The Red Death]]'' (1964) - Gino\n* ''[[The Beauty Jungle]]'' (1964) - Harry\n* ''[[The Heroes of Telemark]]'' (1965) - Arne\n* ''The Legend of Young Dick Turpin'' (1966) - [[Dick Turpin]]\n* ''The Winter's Tale'' (1968) - [[Florizel (The Winter's Tale)|Florizel]] / Archidamas\n* ''[[Von Richthofen and Brown|The Red Baron]]'' (1971) - Murphy\n* ''[[Quest for Love (1971 film)|Quest for Love]]'' (1971) - Johnny Prescott\n* ''[[Nobody Ordered Love]]'' (1972) - Jacques Legrand\n* ''[[King Lear (2008 TV film)|King Lear]]'' (2008) - Gentleman\n* ''Masterpiece'' (2010) - Suit on TV 1\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidcweston.co.uk/ David Weston's website]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0922935|name=David Weston}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weston, David}}\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:People educated at Alleyn's School]]\n[[Category:National Youth Theatre members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n'''David Weston''' (born 28 July 1938, [[London]]) is an English actor, director and author. Since graduating from [[RADA]] in 1961<ref>{{Cite web|title=RADA Graduate Directory |url=http://www.rada.org/alumni/directory.aspx?id=108&frm=y&sur=Weston&nme=David&sub=&ttl=&yr= |accessdate=4 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210010757/http://www.rada.org/alumni/directory.aspx?id=108 |archivedate=10 February 2010 }}</ref> (having won the Silver Medal for that year)<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Awards at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\n  | page = 15\n  | newspaper = The Times\n  | location = London\n  | date = 21 July 1961\n}}</ref> he has acted in numerous film, television and stage productions, including twenty-seven plays in [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s canon and prominent guest roles in two [[Doctor Who]] serials. With [[Michael Croft]] he was a founder member of the [[National Youth Theatre]].<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Jardine\n  | first = Cassandra\n  | title = A new HQ honours the National Youth Theatre's founder\n  | pages =\n  | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph\n  | location = London\n  | date = 28 February 2009\n}}</ref> Much of his directing work has been for that organisation; he has directed also at the [[Regent's Park]] [[Regent's Park Open Air Theatre|Open Air Theatre]] and a number of other theatres in London. He wrote and narrated a series of non-fiction audio books, including ''Shakespeare His Life and Work'' which won the 2001 [https://web.archive.org/web/20090202124736/http://ibpa-online.org/custom/benfranklin/benfranklin.aspx Benjamin Franklin Award] for best audio non-fiction book.\n\n==Early career==\nWeston was educated at [[Alleyn's School]], [[Dulwich]], during the time that Michael Croft, founder of the [[National Youth Theatre]], was there creating drama of a very high standard.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Edward Alleyn Club - Theatre |url=http://www.edwardalleynclub.com/en/Theatre/ |accessdate=7 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126054710/http://www.edwardalleynclub.com/en/Theatre/ |archivedate=26 November 2009 }}</ref> In 1956 Croft directed a school production of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]]'', which, when revived as a [[National Youth Theatre|NYT]] production at the [[Toynbee Hall]] Theatre the following year, attracted the attention of the national press. Weston played [[Falstaff]], a character singled out by ''[[The Times]]'' in its praise of the play's comedy.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Youth Theatre\n  | pages = 3\n  | newspaper = The Times\n  | location = London\n  | date = 23 April 1957\n}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1960 Weston played Mark Antony in Shakespeare's ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'' at the [[Queen's Theatre]], [[Shaftesbury Avenue]]. Directed by Croft and given in [[modern dress]], this was only the second appearance by the company of the [[National Youth Theatre|NYT]] in [[West End of London|London's West End]]. [[John Shrapnel]] played Caesar, Neil Stacy Brutus and Alan Allkins Cassius. The play was judged a \"youthful success\" by the theatre critic of ''[[The Times]]''; Weston's performance was said to have successfully caught an opportunist spirit effectually hidden by a rough charm.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Modern Dress Caesar\n  | pages =\n  | newspaper = The Times\n  | location = London\n  | date = 12 August 1960\n}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Times]]'' was more muted in its praise of the ''[[Electra (Sophocles)|Electra]]'' and ''[[Oedipus Rex]]'' of [[Sophocles]] in a double bill put on by [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art|RADA]] at its Vanbrugh Theatre, [[Bloomsbury]] in February 1961.  Weston played [[Creon]] in ''Oedipus Rex''; his bluff characterisation was described as strongly supportive.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Off-beat Electra\n  | pages =\n  | newspaper = The Times\n  | location = London\n  | date = 7 February 1961\n}}</ref>\n\nWeston's first television appearance was as Romeo in a production for schools of Shakespeare's [[Romeo and Juliet]]; [[Jane Asher]] played Juliet.<ref>{{Cite web\n |title       = Loose Cannon's Hall Of Fame: David Weston\n |url         = http://www.recons.com/biogs/weston.htm\n |accessdate  = 4 February 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100111181808/http://www.recons.com/biogs/weston.htm\n |archivedate = 11 January 2010\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref>\n==Writing==\nIn 2011 Weston published ''Covering McKellen: An Understudy's Tale'', a memoir of the year he spent as [[Ian McKellen]]'s understudy in the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]'s tour of [[King Lear]] directed by [[Sir Trevor Nunn]].<ref>{{Cite book\n  | title = Covering McKellen: An Understudy's Tale\n  | last = Weston\n  | first = David\n  | year = 2011\n  | publisher = Rickshaw Publishing \n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-9565368-0-8}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Weston published ''Covering Shakespeare: An Actor's Saga of Near Misses and Dogged Endurance'', a memoir of his experiences performing in productions of Shakespeare's plays.<ref>{{Cite book\n  | title = Covering Shakespeare: An Actor's Saga of Near Misses and Dogged Endurance\n  | last = Weston\n  | first = David\n  | year = 2014\n  | publisher = Oberon Books\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-1783190645}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[That Kind of Girl]]'' (1963) - Keith Murray\n* ''[[Doctor in Distress (film)|Doctor In Distress]]'' (1963) - Dr Bell\n* ''[[80,000 Suspects]]'' (1963) - Brian Davis (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Informers (1963 film)|The Informers]]'' (1963) - Young constable (uncredited)\n* ''[[Witchcraft (1964 film)|Witchcraft]]'' (1964) - Todd Lanier\n* ''[[Becket (1964 film)|Becket]]'' (1964) - Brother John\n* ''[[The Masque of the Red Death (1964 film)|The Masque of The Red Death]]'' (1964) - Gino\n* ''[[The Beauty Jungle]]'' (1964) - Harry\n* ''[[The Heroes of Telemark]]'' (1965) - Arne\n* ''The Legend of Young Dick Turpin'' (1966) - [[Dick Turpin]]\n* ''The Winter's Tale'' (1968) - [[Florizel (The Winter's Tale)|Florizel]] / Archidamas\n* ''[[Von Richthofen and Brown|The Red Baron]]'' (1971) - Murphy\n* ''[[Quest for Love (1971 film)|Quest for Love]]'' (1971) - Johnny Prescott\n* ''[[Nobody Ordered Love]]'' (1972) - Jacques Legrand\n* ''[[King Lear (2008 TV film)|King Lear]]'' (2008) - Gentleman\n* ''Masterpiece'' (2010) - Suit on TV 1\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidcweston.co.uk/ David Weston's website]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0922935|name=David Weston}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weston, David}}\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:People educated at Alleyn's School]]\n[[Category:National Youth Theatre members]]\n", "name_user": "Emilrubin", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly career)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Weston_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:SirJohnHotham 1stBt ByCornelis Janssen.jpg|thumb|Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet, portrait by [[Cornelius Johnson (artist)|Cornelius Janssens]]]]\n[[File:John Hotham 1st Baronet.jpg|thumb|Hotham in his role as Governor of Hull]]\n[[File:HothamArms.svg|thumb|Arms of  Hotham: ''Barry of ten argent and azure, on a canton or a Cornish chough proper''<ref>Source: Montague-Smith, P.W. (ed.), Debrett's Peerage, Baronetage, Knightage and Companionage,  Kelly's Directories Ltd, Kingston-upon-Thames, 1968, p.590</ref>]]\n[[File:Beverley Gate plaque, Hull July 2018.jpg|thumb|Commemorative plaque, Beverley Gate, Hull]] \n'''Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet''' (circa July 1589 \u2013 3 January 1645) of [[Scorborough]] Hall, near [[Driffield]], Yorkshire, was an [[English people|English]] [[Member of Parliament]] who was [[List of Governors of Kingston-upon-Hull|Governor of Hull]] in 1642 shortly before the start of the [[English Civil War|Civil War]]. He refused to allow King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] or any member of his entourage to enter the town, thereby depriving the king of access to the large arsenal contained within. Later in the Civil War he and his son [[John Hotham the younger]] were accused of treachery to the Parliamentarian cause, found guilty and executed on [[Tower Hill]].<ref>Debrett's Peerage,  1968, p.591</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nHe was born in 1589<ref>probably in July 1589, Scott,2008</ref> the second but only surviving son<ref>Healy</ref> of  [[John Hotham (died c. 1609)|John Hotham]] (1540\u20131609) of Scorborough, who in 1584 had been elected a Member of Parliament for [[Scarborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Scarborough]] in Yorkshire. His mother has been variously given as Julian Stanhope, a daughter of [[Michael Stanhope (died 1552)|Sir Michael Stanhope]] of [[Shelford, Nottinghamshire|Shelford]], [[Nottinghamshire]]{{sfn| Chisholm|1911|p=803}} or as Jane Legard, a daughter of Richard Legard of Rysome, Yorkshire.<ref>Scott; Healy</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe fought on the continent of Europe during the early part of the [[Thirty Years' War]].{{sfn| Chisholm|1911|p=803}} In 1622 he was made a [[baronet]]. He was elected a Member of Parliament for [[Beverley (UK Parliament constituency)|Beverley]] in the five Parliaments between 1625 and 1640, and served as [[Sheriff of Yorkshire]] in 1634. In 1639 he was deprived by the king of his office of Governor of [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], and joining the parliamentary party, he refused to pay [[Ship money|ship-money]]. In January 1642 Hotham was ordered by Parliament to seize the town of Hull, where there was a large store of munitions of war; this was at once carried out by his son [[John Hotham the younger]]. Hotham senior took command of Hull and in April 1642 refused to admit King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] to the town. Later he promised his prisoner, [[George Digby, 2nd Earl of Bristol]], that he would surrender the town to the king, but when Charles appeared again he refused a second time and drove away the besiegers.{{sfn| Chisholm|1911|p=803}}\n\nMeanwhile, Hotham the younger was taking an active part in the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] in [[Yorkshire]] and [[Lincolnshire]], but was soon at variance with other parliamentary leaders, especially with [[Ferdinando Fairfax, 2nd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Lord Fairfax]] and his son Sir [[Thomas Fairfax, 3rd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Thomas Fairfax]], and complaints about his conduct and that of his troops were made by [[Oliver Cromwell]] and by Colonel [[John Hutchinson (Colonel)|John Hutchinson]]. Soon both the Hothams were corresponding with the [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]], and Hotham the younger was probably ready to betray Hull; these proceedings became known to Parliament, and in June 1643 father and son were captured and taken to [[London]].{{sfn| Chisholm|1911|p=803}}\n\n==Death & burial==\n[[File:John Hotham Tomb South Dalton.jpg|thumb|Monument to Sir John Hotham in St Mary's Church, [[South Dalton]] (near Scorborough),<ref>http://www.daltonestate.co.uk/history</ref> supported by figures of the [[cardinal virtues]]]]\nAfter a long delay they were tried by [[court-martial]], were found guilty and were sentenced to death. The younger Hotham was beheaded at [[Tower Hill]] on 2 January 1645, and despite of efforts made by the [[House of Lords]] and the [[Presbyterians]] to save him, his father suffered the same fate on the following day. Both were buried at the nearby church of [[All Hallows-by-the-Tower]]. {{sfn|Scott|2008}} A tomb monument was erected in his memory in St Mary's Church, South Dalton. The baronetcy passed to Sir John's grandson [[Sir John Hotham, 2nd Baronet]], the son of Hotham the younger.\n\n===Marriages & progeny===\nSir John married five times and had sixteen children of whom six sons and three daughters survived childhood.{{sfn|Scott|2008}}\n*Firstly, on 16 February 1607, to Katherine Rodes, daughter of Sir John Rodes of [[Barlborough]], Derbyshire. By Katherine, who brought a [[dowry]] of 1,000 [[Mark (currency)|marks]], he had two sons and two daughters, who all predeceased their father,<ref name=HP>{{cite web|url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/hotham-sir-john-1589-1645|title= Hotham, Sir John, 1st Bt. (1589-1645), of Scorborough, Yorks.; later of Fyling Hall, Yorks.|publisher= [[History of Parliament]] Online|accessdate = 31 January 2017}}</ref> including:\n**[[John Hotham the younger]], eldest son and [[heir apparent]], who with his father was accused of treachery, found guilty and executed.{{sfn|Scott|2008}}\n*Secondly, on 16 July 1614 to Anne Rokeby, daughter and heiress of [[Ralph Rokeby (died 1595)|Ralph Rokeby]] (died 1595), Deputy Secretary of the Council in the North 1587\u201395, by whom he had three sons, including:\n**Rev. [[Charles Hotham (priest)|Charles Hotham]] (1615\u2013 c.1672), Rector of [[Wigan]], a Cambridge scholar and author of ''Ad Philosophiam Teutonicam Manuductio'' (1648). He supported Parliament during the Civil War, and was ejected as a minister shortly after the [[Restoration of the Monarchy]].{{sfn|Scott|2008}}\n**[[Durant Hotham]] (1617\u20131691), a lawyer, landowner, and [[East Riding of Yorkshire|East Riding]] magistrate,{{sfn|Scott|2008}} author of a ''Life'' of [[Jakob Boehme]] (1654).<ref name=HP/>\n*Thirdly he married Frances Legard, daughter of John Legard, of the [[City of London]] London and of [[Ganton, North Yorkshire]], a member of the [[Worshipful Company of Haberdashers]], by whom he had  three daughters, who all predeceased their father.<ref name=HP/> \n*Fourthly, on 27 October 1631, he married Katherine Bamburgh ( d. 31 August 1634<ref name=HP/>), a daughter of [[Sir William Bamburgh, 1st Baronet]] of [[Howsham, North Yorkshire]], and widow of Sir Thomas Norcliffe of [[Langton, North Yorkshire]]. By Katherine Bamburgh he had two daughters, one of whom predeceased their father.\n*Fifthly, on 7 May 1635, he married Sarah Anlaby, a daughter of Thomas Anlaby of [[Etton, East Riding of Yorkshire|Etton, Yorkshire]], by whom he had four daughters.<ref name=HP/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{cite ODNB |last=Scott |first=David |title=Hotham, Sir John, first baronet (1589\u20131645) |origyear=2004 |date=January 2008 |id=13852}}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Hotham, Sir John |volume=13 |page=803}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commons category|Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet}}\n{{DNB poster|Hotham, John Sr. (d.1645)}}\n* {{Citation| last=Lundy |first=Darryl |date=5 August 2012|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p22438.htm#i224375 |title=Sir John Hotham, 1st Bt |page=22438 \u00a7224375}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box \n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Beverley (UK Parliament constituency)|Beverley]] \n| before=  [[Henry Carey, 2nd Earl of Monmouth|Sir Henry Carey]]\n| before2= [[Edmund Scott]]\n| with= [[William Alford (MP)|William Alford]] \n| years=1625\u20131629\n| after= Parliament suspended until 1640\n}}\n{{succession box \n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Beverley (UK Parliament constituency)|Beverley]] \n| before=Parliament suspended since 1629\n| with= [[Michael Warton (died 1645)|Michael Warton]]\n| years=1640\u20131643\n| after= [[Michael Warton (died 1645)|Michael Warton]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|en-bt}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Hotham baronets|Baronet]]<br>'''(of Scorborough)''' \n       | years  = 1622\u20131645}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Sir John Hotham, 2nd Baronet|John Hotham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hotham, John}}\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1645 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Beverley]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England|Hotham, John, 1st Baronet]]\n[[Category:Roundheads]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Executed people from North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People executed by the British military by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People killed in the English Civil War]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1625]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1626]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1628\u20131629]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640 (April)]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640\u20131648]]\n[[Category:English politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:SirJohnHotham 1stBt ByCornelis Janssen.jpg|thumb|Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet, portrait by [[Cornelius Johnson (artist)|Cornelius Janssens]]]]\n[[File:John Hotham 1st Baronet.jpg|thumb|Hotham in his role as Governor of Hull]]\n[[File:HothamArms.svg|thumb|Arms of  Hotham: ''Barry of ten argent and azure, on a canton or a Cornish chough proper''<ref>Source: Montague-Smith, P.W. (ed.), Debrett's Peerage, Baronetage, Knightage and Companionage,  Kelly's Directories Ltd, Kingston-upon-Thames, 1968, p.590</ref>]]\n[[File:Beverley Gate plaque, Hull July 2018.jpg|thumb|Commemorative plaque, Beverley Gate, Hull]] \n'''Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet''' (circa July 1589 \u2013 3 January 1645) of [[Scorborough]] Hall, near [[Driffield]], Yorkshire, was an [[English people|English]] [[Member of Parliament]] who was [[List of Governors of Kingston-upon-Hull|Governor of Hull]] in 1642 shortly before the start of the [[English Civil War|Civil War]]. He refused to allow King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] or any member of his entourage to enter the town, thereby depriving the king of access to the large arsenal contained within. Later in the Civil War he and his son [[John Hotham the younger]] were accused of treachery to the Parliamentarian cause, found guilty and executed on [[Tower Hill]].<ref>Debrett's Peerage,  1968, p.591</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nHe was born in 1589<ref>probably in July 1589, Scott,2008</ref> the second but only surviving son<ref>Healy</ref> of  [[John Hotham (died c. 1609)|John Hotham]] (1540\u20131609) of Scorborough, who in 1584 had been elected a Member of Parliament for [[Scarborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Scarborough]] in Yorkshire. His mother has been variously given as Julian Stanhope, a daughter of [[Michael Stanhope (died 1552)|Sir Michael Stanhope]] of [[Shelford, Nottinghamshire|Shelford]], [[Nottinghamshire]]{{sfn| Chisholm|1911|p=803}} or as Jane Legard, a daughter of Richard Legard of Rysome, Yorkshire.<ref>Scott; Healy</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe fought on the continent of Europe during the early part of the [[Thirty Years' War]].{{sfn| Chisholm|1911|p=803}} In 1622 he was made a [[baronet]]. He was elected a Member of Parliament for [[Beverley (UK Parliament constituency)|Beverley]] in the five Parliaments between 1625 and 1640, and served as [[Sheriff of Yorkshire]] in 1634. In 1639 he was deprived by the king of his office of Governor of [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], and joining the parliamentary party, he refused to pay [[Ship money|ship-money]]. In January 1642 Hotham was ordered by Parliament to seize the town of Hull, where there was a large store of munitions of war; this was at once carried out by his son [[John Hotham the younger]]. Hotham senior took command of Hull and in April 1642 refused to admit King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] to the town. Later he promised his prisoner, [[George Digby, 2nd Earl of Bristol]], that he would surrender the town to the king, but when Charles appeared again he refused a second time and drove away the besiegers.{{sfn| Chisholm|1911|p=803}}\n\nMeanwhile, Hotham the younger was taking an active part in the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] in [[Yorkshire]] and [[Lincolnshire]], but was soon at variance with other parliamentary leaders, especially with [[Ferdinando Fairfax, 2nd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Lord Fairfax]] and his son Sir [[Thomas Fairfax, 3rd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Thomas Fairfax]], and complaints about his conduct and that of his troops were made by [[Oliver Cromwell]] and by Colonel [[John Hutchinson (Colonel)|John Hutchinson]]. Soon both the Hothams were corresponding with the [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]], and Hotham the younger was probably ready to betray Hull; these proceedings became known to Parliament, and in June 1643 father and son were captured and taken to [[London]].{{sfn| Chisholm|1911|p=803}}\n\n==Death & burial==\n[[File:John Hotham Tomb South Dalton.jpg|thumb|Monument to Sir John Hotham in St Mary's Church, [[South Dalton]] (near Scorborough),<ref>http://www.daltonestate.co.uk/history</ref> supported by figures of the [[cardinal virtues]]]]\nAfter a long delay they were tried by [[court-martial]], were found guilty and were sentenced to death. The younger Hotham was beheaded at [[Tower Hill]] on 2 January 1645, and despite of efforts made by the [[House of Lords]] and the [[Presbyterians]] to save him, his father suffered the same fate on the following day. Both were buried at the nearby church of [[All Hallows-by-the-Tower]]. {{sfn|Scott|2008}} A tomb monument was erected in his memory in St Mary's Church, South Dalton. The baronetcy passed to Sir John's grandson [[Sir John Hotham, 2nd Baronet]], the son of Hotham the younger.\n\n===Marriages & progeny===\nSir John married five times and had sixteen children of whom six sons and three daughters survived childhood.{{sfn|Scott|2008}}\n*Firstly, on 16 February 1607, to Katherine Rodes, daughter of Sir John Rodes of [[Barlborough]], Derbyshire. By Katherine, who brought a [[dowry]] of 1,000 [[Mark (currency)|marks]], he had two sons and two daughters, who all predeceased their father,<ref name=HP>{{cite web|url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/hotham-sir-john-1589-1645|title= Hotham, Sir John, 1st Bt. (1589-1645), of Scorborough, Yorks.; later of Fyling Hall, Yorks.|publisher= [[History of Parliament]] Online|accessdate = 31 January 2017}}</ref> including:\n**[[John Hotham the younger]], eldest son and [[heir apparent]], who with his father was accused of treachery, found guilty and executed.{{sfn|Scott|2008}}\n*Secondly, on 16 July 1614 to Anne Rokeby, daughter and heiress of [[Ralph Rokeby (died 1595)|Ralph Rokeby]] (died 1595), Deputy Secretary of the Council in the North 1587-95, by whom he had three sons, including:\n**Rev. [[Charles Hotham (priest)|Charles Hotham]] (1615\u2013 c.1672), Rector of [[Wigan]], a Cambridge scholar and author of ''Ad Philosophiam Teutonicam Manuductio'' (1648). He supported Parliament during the Civil War, and was ejected as a minister shortly after the [[Restoration of the Monarchy]].{{sfn|Scott|2008}}\n**[[Durant Hotham]] (1617\u20131691), a lawyer, landowner, and [[East Riding of Yorkshire|East Riding]] magistrate,{{sfn|Scott|2008}} author of a ''Life'' of [[Jakob Boehme]] (1654).<ref name=HP/>\n*Thirdly he married Frances Legard, daughter of John Legard, of the [[City of London]] London and of [[Ganton, North Yorkshire]], a member of the [[Worshipful Company of Haberdashers]], by whom he had  three daughters, who all predeceased their father.<ref name=HP/> \n*Fourthly, on 27 October 1631, he married Katherine Bamburgh ( d. 31 August 1634<ref name=HP/>), a daughter of [[Sir William Bamburgh, 1st Baronet]] of [[Howsham, North Yorkshire]], and widow of Sir Thomas Norcliffe of [[Langton, North Yorkshire]]. By Katherine Bamburgh he had two daughters, one of whom predeceased their father.\n*Fifthly, on 7 May 1635, he married Sarah Anlaby, a daughter of Thomas Anlaby of [[Etton, East Riding of Yorkshire|Etton, Yorkshire]], by whom he had four daughters.<ref name=HP/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{cite ODNB |last=Scott |first=David |title=Hotham, Sir John, first baronet (1589\u20131645) |origyear=2004 |date=January 2008 |id=13852}}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Hotham, Sir John |volume=13 |page=803}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commons category|Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet}}\n{{DNB poster|Hotham, John Sr. (d.1645)}}\n* {{Citation| last=Lundy |first=Darryl |date=5 August 2012|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p22438.htm#i224375 |title=Sir John Hotham, 1st Bt |page=22438 \u00a7224375}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box \n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Beverley (UK Parliament constituency)|Beverley]] \n| before=  [[Henry Carey, 2nd Earl of Monmouth|Sir Henry Carey]]\n| before2= [[Edmund Scott]]\n| with= [[William Alford (MP)|William Alford]] \n| years=1625\u20131629\n| after= Parliament suspended until 1640\n}}\n{{succession box \n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Beverley (UK Parliament constituency)|Beverley]] \n| before=Parliament suspended since 1629\n| with= [[Michael Warton (died 1645)|Michael Warton]]\n| years=1640\u20131643\n| after= [[Michael Warton (died 1645)|Michael Warton]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|en-bt}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Hotham baronets|Baronet]]<br>'''(of Scorborough)''' \n       | years  = 1622\u20131645}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Sir John Hotham, 2nd Baronet|John Hotham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hotham, John}}\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1645 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Beverley]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England|Hotham, John, 1st Baronet]]\n[[Category:Roundheads]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Executed people from North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People executed by the British military by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People killed in the English Civil War]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1625]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1626]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1628\u20131629]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640 (April)]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640\u20131648]]\n[[Category:English politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarriages & progeny:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1587-95 \u2192 1587\u201395", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_John_Hotham,_1st_Baronet"}
